         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>353</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... you evoke in me the wish to ... these good ones</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">Du rufst [in] mir den Wunsch hervor, diesen guten ...</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">You evoke the desire [in] me, this good ... [to ... this good...?]</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>330</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(fathe)r, brother, property, power, and the dignity of a householder</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">MaitrHami 13, 9-10</note><note type="philcomment">This fragment contains part of the thirteenth act of the Maitreyasamitināṭaka; an Uy. parallel is MaitrHami XIII, 9a19-10a15f. See also <bibl><title corresp="ref:pinault1999"/><citedRange>201</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note corresp="#b7" type="philcomment">Ilya Itkin (p.c., 20 July 2016) suggests restoring <hi>(sä)rk</hi>, which is supported by the fact that the expression "sickness, old age and death" is also attested in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-yqi10"/> a6, albeit with the word <w lemmaRef="A_wraske"/> for "sickness" instead of <w lemmaRef="A_särk"/>. On the other hand, the restoration <hi>(sä)rk</hi> conflicts with the Uyghur translation, which only mentions old age and death: <hi>qarïmaq ölmäkn(i)ng</hi> (MaitrHami XIII, 10a13, cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:gengetal1991"/><citedRange>280</citedRange></bibl>).</note></p>
         </div>
